Msg.Desc: Missing layer thickness information in the layout cross section.

All etch and dielectric layers must have a non-zero layer thickness assigned for NC backdrilling to be able to function.
Thicknesses can be defined using the Layout Cross Section interface.

Thieving could not be generated within the specified outline.
Msg.ExtDesc:
There were unspecified problems in trying to determine what areas within the specified thieving outline could in fact be filled with the thieving pattern. It is typically due to complexities involved with what is on the design and within the specified outline that need to be avoided by the thieving.
Suggestions to try and get thieving generated are to try a somewhat different outline, or to instead try a number of smaller outlines to reduce the complexity of what is within each outline.

Msg.Desc: Specified 'From Layer' is not valid with the current 'To Layer'.
Msg.ExtDesc: Backdrilling cannot have the 'From Layer' set to the top layer if the current 'To Layer' is the bottom layer. Similarly the 'From Layer' cannot be set to the bottom layer if the current 'To Layer' is the top layer. In other words backdrilling through all layers of a design is not allowed.

Msg.Desc: Specified 'To Layer' is not valid with the current 'From Layer'.
Msg.ExtDesc:
Backdrilling cannot have the 'To Layer' set to the bottom layer if the current 'From Layer' is the top layer. Similarly the 'To Layer' cannot be set to the top layer if the current 'From Layer' is the bottom layer. In other words backdrilling through all layers of a design is not allowed.
The 'To Layer' can also not be set to the top or bottom layer of a design if the current 'From Layer' is an internal layer of the design.

Msg.Desc: Design contains padstacks with a plating status of 'Optional' that are being ignored by backdrilling.
Msg.ExtDesc: Backdrilling only looks at pins and vias whose padstacks have a plating status of 'Plated' in the padstack editor. Pins and vias whose padstacks have a plating status of 'Non-Plated' or 'Optional' will be ignored for backdrilling purposes.

Holes will generally not appear in a 'Black and white' plot.
Msg.ExtDesc:
Holes are currently enabled for display/plotting, but will generally not appear in a plot as 'Black and white' plots have been enabled in Plot Setup. Holes are displayed in the currently specified color, but any color (including white) is converted to black for a black and white plot. A padless hole will appear though as the black hole will not be inside a black pad.
Holes will appear in a 'Color' plot, likely even if a color plot is sent to a non-color printer if the plot in fact comes out grayscale. The exception to this however with 'Color' plots would be a padless hole where the color of the hole and the color of the plot background are the same (e.g. a white padless hole that is plotted on white paper).
